def getQuartileCounts(col):
    print('Quartile Analysis of ', col)
    print()
    Min = concreteData[col].min()
    Max = concreteData[col].max()
    Std = concreteData[col].std()
    Mean = concreteData[col].mean()
    Median = concreteData[col].median()
    Q1 = concreteData[col].quantile(q=0.25)
    Q2 = concreteData[col].quantile(q=0.50)
    Q3 = concreteData[col].quantile(q=0.75)
    IQR = Q3-Q1
    Minimum = Q1 - (1.5 * IQR)
    Maximum = Q3 + (1.5 * IQR)
    LeftOutlierCount = concreteData[concreteData[col]<Minimum].shape[0]
    Q1Count = concreteData[(concreteData[col]>=Minimum) & (concreteData[col]<=Q1)].shape[0]
    Q2Count = concreteData[(concreteData[col]>Q1) & (concreteData[col]<=Q2)].shape[0]
    Q3Count = concreteData[(concreteData[col]>Q2) & (concreteData[col]<=Q3)].shape[0]
    Q4Count = concreteData[(concreteData[col]>Q3) & (concreteData[col]<=Maximum)].shape[0]
    RightOutlierCount = concreteData[concreteData[col]>Maximum].shape[0]
    print('Min ', Min, " Value count: ", concreteData[concreteData[col] == Min].shape[0])
    print('Max ', Max, " Value count: ", concreteData[concreteData[col] == Max].shape[0])
    print()
    print('Standard Deviation ', Std)
    print('Mean ', Mean)
    print('Median ', Median)
    print()
    print('25th percentile Q1 ', Q1)
    print('50th percentile Q2 ', Q2)
    print('75th percentile Q3 ', Q3)
    print('IQR ', IQR)
    print('Minimum = Q1 - 1.5*IQR = ', Minimum)
    print('Maximum = Q3 + 1.5*IQR = ', Maximum)
    print()
    print('Left outlier count i.e. < Minimum  ', LeftOutlierCount)
    print('>= Minimum and <= Q1 count         ', Q1Count)
    print('> Q1 and <= Q2 count               ', Q2Count)
    print('> Q2 and <= Q3 count               ', Q3Count)
    print('> Q3 and <= Maximum                ', Q4Count)
    print('Right outlier count i.e. > Maximum ', RightOutlierCount)
    print('Total Outliers ', (LeftOutlierCount+RightOutlierCount), '  ', (LeftOutlierCount+RightOutlierCount)*100/rowCount, '%', ' of total records')
    print()
    if(Mean > Median):
        print('Distribution is Right Skewed because Mean > Median')
    elif(Mean < Median):
        print('Distribution is Left Skewed because Mean < Median')
    else:
        print('Distribution is Symmetric because Mean = Median')
        
        
def plotUnivariate(col, pltType):
    if (pltType == 'box-dist'):
        fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=[15,5])
        fig.tight_layout(pad=5.0)
        getQuartileCounts(col)
        sns.boxplot(data=concreteData, x=col, ax=axes[0]);
        sns.distplot(concreteData[col], ax=axes[1]);

# Bivariate - BoxPlots & Density Curves & Scatter Plots
def plotBivariate(col1, col2):
    figure, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(15,10))
    figure.tight_layout(pad=5.0)

    sns.boxplot(data=concreteDataScaled, x=col1, color="r", ax=axes[0,0])
    sns.boxplot(data=concreteDataScaled, x=col2, color="b", ax=axes[0,0]);
    
    sns.kdeplot(concreteDataScaled[col1], shade=True, color="r", ax=axes[0,1])
    sns.kdeplot(concreteDataScaled[col2], shade=True, color="b", ax=axes[0,1]);
    
    sns.distplot(concreteDataScaled[col1], color="r", kde=False, ax=axes[1,0])
    sns.distplot(concreteDataScaled[col2], color="b", kde=False, ax=axes[1,0]);
    
    sns.scatterplot(data=concreteDataScaled, x=col1, y=col2, ax=axes[1,1]);

  • Blast Furnace Slag (slag) and Concrete compressive strength are very weakly positively correlated. Degree of Correlation 0.134829
  • Fly Ash and Concrete compressive strength are very weakly negatively correlated. Degree of Correlation -0.105755
  • Water and Concrete compressive strength are very weakly negatively correlated. Degree of Correlation -0.289633
  • Superplasticizer (superplastic) and Concrete compressive strength are positively correlated. Degree of Correlation 0.366079
  • Coarse Aggregate (coarseagg) and Concrete compressive strength are very weakly negatively correlated. Degree of Correlation -0.164935
  • Fine Aggregate and Concrete compressive strength are very weakly negatively correlated. Degree of Correlation -0.167241
  • Age and Concrete compressive strength are weakly positively correlated. Degree of Correlation 0.328873

def forwardFeatureSuggestor (model, modelName, featureCount, x_train, y_train, cvFolds):
    selector = sfs(estimator=model, k_features=featureCount, forward=True, scoring='r2', cv=cvFolds)
    selector.fit(x_train, y_train)
    metricsDict = selector.get_metric_dict()
    scoreDF = pd.DataFrame(metricsDict).T
    #print(scoreDF)
    maxAvgScore = scoreDF['avg_score'].max()
    suggestedFeatures = np.array(scoreDF[scoreDF['avg_score']==maxAvgScore].feature_names)
    
    plot_sfs(metricsDict)
    plt.title(modelName + ': Sequential Forward Selection (w. R^2)')
    return suggestedFeatures

def findScoreAndCoeffs (model, modelName, x_train, y_train, x_test, y_test, printCoeffs=True):
    model.fit(x_train, y_train)
    print(modelName, " Model: ")
    print()
    print("Training Score = ", model.score(x_train, y_train), " Testing Score = ", model.score(x_test, y_test))
    print()
    if(printCoeffs):
        for idx, col_name in enumerate(x_train.columns):
            if(modelName == "Lasso Regression" or modelName == 'Linear SVR Regression'):
                print("The coefficient for {} is {}".format(col_name, model.coef_[idx]))
            else:
                print("The coefficient for {} is {}".format(col_name, model.coef_[0][idx]))

def collectScoreWithKFold(model, modelName, x_train, y_train, polyData):
    result = cross_validate(estimator=model, X= x_train, y=y_train, cv=kfold, return_estimator=True)
    resultDF = pd.DataFrame(result)
    maxScore = resultDF['test_score'].max()
    meanScore = resultDF['test_score'].mean()
    stdScore = resultDF['test_score'].std()
    estimator = list(resultDF[resultDF['test_score']==maxScore]['estimator'])[0]
    #print(resultDF)
    resultFrame = pd.Series([modelName, maxScore*100, meanScore*100, stdScore*100, x_train.shape[1], polyData, estimator], index=kFoldResults.columns)
    return resultFrame

Hyperparameter Tuning¶

Algorithms to be used¶

  • Grid Search - Providing small param space for GridSearchCV as it takes lot of time to complete all iterations.
  • Random Search - Providing max possible param space for RandomSearchCV as it is faster and try hit parameters at random.
In [81]:
# Dataframe to store Hyperparameter Tuning results

hyperResults = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Regressor', 'SearchCV', 'Accuracy %', ' (+-) Deviation %', 'Features', 
                                     'Has Polynomial Features', 'Param Space Size', 'Best Params'])
In [82]:
def tuneHyperParams (model, modelName, x_train, y_train, params, polyData, searchAlgo, paramSpaceSize):
    if(searchAlgo == 'GridSearchCV'):
        modelCV = GridSearchCV(estimator=model, param_grid=params, cv=folds)
    elif(searchAlgo == 'RandomizedSearchCV'):
        modelCV = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=model, param_distributions=params, cv=folds, n_iter=1000)
        
    modelCV.fit(x_train, y_train)
    modelCVResult = pd.DataFrame(modelCV.cv_results_)
    modelCVMaxScore = modelCVResult['mean_test_score'].max()
    modelCVDeviation = np.array(modelCVResult[modelCVResult['mean_test_score'] == modelCVMaxScore]['std_test_score'])
    resultFrame = pd.Series([modelName, searchAlgo, modelCVMaxScore*100, modelCVDeviation[0]*100, x_train.shape[1], 
                             polyData, paramSpaceSize, modelCV.best_params_], index=hyperResults.columns)
    return resultFrame

model = None

elif(bestRegressor == 'Ridge Regression'):
    model = Ridge()
